---
import MoneyPageLayout from '../layouts/MoneyPageLayout.astro';

const faqs = [
  { q: 'How do I apply for an ITIN?', a: 'File IRS Form W-7 with proof of identity and foreign status, usually alongside a federal tax return. You can submit by mail, through an IRS-authorized Certifying Acceptance Agent (CAA), or at an IRS Taxpayer Assistance Center.' },
  { q: 'How long does it take to get an ITIN?', a: 'The IRS typically processes ITIN applications in about 7 to 11 weeks, and longer during tax season (January–April). Applying outside peak season is faster.' },
  { q: 'What documents do I need for an ITIN?', a: 'A completed Form W-7, a valid passport (or two alternative IDs), and usually a federal tax return. A passport is the only document that proves both identity and foreign status on its own.' },
  { q: 'Does it cost money to get an ITIN?', a: 'The IRS does not charge a fee for Form W-7 itself. Certifying Acceptance Agents and tax preparers may charge for their help, but you can also apply directly for free.' },
  { q: 'Do I need to renew my ITIN?', a: 'ITINs not used on a federal tax return for three consecutive years expire, as do certain older ITINs. If yours has expired, file Form W-7 to renew before using it on a return.' },
];
const quickAnswer =
  'To get an ITIN, file IRS Form W-7 with proof of identity and foreign status (a passport is ideal), usually along with a federal tax return. Submit by mail, through an IRS-authorized Certifying Acceptance Agent, or at a Taxpayer Assistance Center. Processing takes about 7–11 weeks. The IRS charges no fee for the form itself.';
---
<MoneyPageLayout
  title="How to Get an ITIN: Step-by-Step Guide (2026)"
  h1="How to Get an ITIN"
  description="Step-by-step guide to applying for an ITIN with IRS Form W-7 — documents required, where to apply, processing time, cost, and renewal."
  path="/how-to-get-an-itin"
  eyebrow="ITIN basics"
  lede="An ITIN is your key to filing taxes, opening accounts, and borrowing in the U.S. without an SSN. Here's exactly how to apply, step by step."
  quickAnswer={quickAnswer}
  faqs={faqs}
>
  <h2>What is an ITIN?</h2>
  <p>An <strong>Individual Taxpayer Identification Number (ITIN)</strong> is a nine-digit tax processing number the IRS issues to people who must file U.S. taxes but aren't eligible for a Social Security Number. It always begins with a 9. An ITIN doesn't grant work authorization or immigration status — but it does open the door to banking, credit, and loans.</p>

  <h2>Step-by-step: how to apply</h2>
  <ol class="lead-list">
    <li><strong>Complete IRS Form W-7</strong> — the "Application for IRS Individual Taxpayer Identification Number."</li>
    <li><strong>Gather your documents</strong> — a valid passport is the simplest, since it proves both identity and foreign status. Without one, you'll need two alternative documents.</li>
    <li><strong>Attach your tax return</strong> — most applicants must include a completed federal return, unless they meet an exception.</li>
    <li><strong>Submit your application</strong> — by mail to the IRS, through a Certifying Acceptance Agent (CAA), or in person at an IRS Taxpayer Assistance Center.</li>
    <li><strong>Wait for your ITIN</strong> — the IRS mails it in about 7–11 weeks.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Three ways to submit</h2>
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Method</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>By mail</td><td>Free, but you must mail original documents or certified copies</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Certifying Acceptance Agent</td><td>Verifies your documents so you keep your passport; may charge a fee</td></tr>
      <tr><td>IRS Taxpayer Assistance Center</td><td>In-person document review by appointment</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>After you get your ITIN</h2>
  <p>Once your ITIN arrives, you can file taxes, open a U.S. bank account, apply for credit cards, and pursue the loans covered across this site. A smart first move is opening a bank account and a secured credit card to start building U.S. credit history right away.</p>

  <p class="form-note">For official forms and the latest requirements, always check IRS.gov. This guide is general information, not tax or legal advice.</p>
</MoneyPageLayout>
